    "M. R. Bave Mehrigadder",
    "Disclaimer: One may notice that there are also a few introductory and anthropological works among this list. These works have been",
    "recommended because they either deal with the esoteric dimensions of Islam as they have influenced the course of Islamic history or help",
    "provide better context for /x/philes who wish to know more about Islamic esotericism but require a better understanding of the cultural and",
    "historical contexts in which these traditions emerged. The compiler of this list has also taken care to try to provide books dealing with the",
    "phenomenon of Islamic esotericism and gnosticism in its generalities and so has not tried to show too much bias to any particular group that",
    "appeals to an esoteric or philosophical approach to Islamic religion. Among these works, one is likely to find views which are not simply fringe",
    "traditions or schools which define themselves as Muslim and/or appeal to the mystical understanding of Islam and its religious sources a",
    "proper chance to represent themselves."
